  "slug": "what-does-my-mum-guilt-actually-want-from-me-journal",
  "title": "What Does My Mum Guilt Actually Want From Me?",
  "subtitle": "A journal prompt set for understanding what the guilt is saying before you answer it",
  "excerpt": "A journal prompt set for the guilt that arrives around mothering. Asks what the guilt actually wants, whether giving it what it asks for would help, and where it came from in the first place.",
  "type": "PRACTICE",
  "sourceNotes": "Written for homemade.education, drawing on maternal psychology literature and the good-enough mother tradition.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A journal prompt set for mum guilt. Not to dismiss it, and not to be flattened by it. The prompts treat the guilt as a signal that has something to say and ask what, exactly, it is saying.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "New to journal prompts? Read ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "journal prompts as practice",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "/mindset/journal-prompts-as-practice"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " first.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The practice",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Warm-up",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 4
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What triggered the guilt today?",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Name the specific thing. Not the general category. The specific moment.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 4
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "On a scale of 0 to 10, how loud is the guilt right now?",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Write the number. Then write one sentence about what makes it that loud.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Closer in",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 4
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "If the guilt could speak, what would it say it wants?",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Write its answer in first person. Let it speak. What is it asking you to do or be?",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 4
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "If you gave it exactly what it wants, would that actually help your children?",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Think clearly about this. Sometimes the answer is yes. Often the answer is no. Guilt has no calibration for what children actually need.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 4
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Whose voice is saying the thing the guilt is saying?",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Is it your mother? A parenting book? The mothers at the school gate? Social media? Your own childhood? Name the voice.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this practice comes from",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Written for homemade.education. Draws on the good-enough mother idea from maternal psychology. The idea comes from the work of D.W. Winnicott in the 1950s and 1960s. Also draws on recent writing about mum guilt as a cultural pattern.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
